@ Kikee_31 -  I hope this will help to find your answer :
"R5 or R5.Line
R5 releases differ from normal releases in that they are a direct Telecine transfer of the film without any of the image processing. They take the information from the DVD disc and sync it to an English version of the film, usually a previously released version. Which means that the sound often isnâ€™t as good as DVDRips. In some cases, R5 DVDs may be released without an English audio track, requiring pirates to use the direct line audio from the filmâ€™s theatrical release. In this case, the pirated release should be tagged with â€œ.LINEâ€ to distinguish it from a release with a DVD audio track."

R5 means a Region 5 DVD (Russian), which is usually a slightly rushed DVD (not digitally cleaned up), somewhat comparable to a studio TS and then applied audio from a ENG source (sometimes previously released TS).

Watchable on a computer, or a large TV you might want to wait for a proper R9 etc DVD.
